      ],
      "reference": {
        "notes": "source_ref: EarthSciData.jl@830435a065f27e99f10bba91107ca1730322cc6b:src/nei2016monthly.jl\n\nUpstream definition:\n  const DELP_DRY_SURFACE_ITP = let\n      delp_data = load(joinpath(@__DIR__, \"mean_domian_delp_dry_surface.jld2\"), \"mean_domian_delp_dry_surface\")\n      domain_lon = collect(-125.0:0.625:-66.875)  # 94 points\n      domain_lat = collect(25.0:0.5:49.0)         # 49 points\n      itp = interpolate((domain_lon, domain_lat), delp_data, Gridded(Linear()))\n      extrapolate(itp, Flat())\n  end\n\n  function delp_dry_surface_itp(lon, lat)\n      lon_deg = rad2deg(lon)\n      lat_deg = rad2deg(lat)\n      return DELP_DRY_SURFACE_ITP(lon_deg, lat_deg)\n  end\n  @register_symbolic delp_dry_surface_itp(lon, lat)\n\nGrid axes:\n  axis_x (lon, 94 pts): -125.0, -124.375, ..., -66.875 (step 0.625 degrees)\n  axis_y (lat, 49 pts): 25.0, 25.5, ..., 49.0 (step 0.5 degrees)\n\nData provenance:\n  Table is the field 'mean_domian_delp_dry_surface' from the precomputed file bundled with EarthSciData.jl.\n  This is the time-mean dry pressure thickness (in hPa, stored as unitless float) of the surface layer.\n\nPhysical interpretation:\n  For GEOS-Chem 72-layer hybrid sigma-pressure, delp_surface is about 10-15 hPa.\n  Lowest over high terrain (Rockies ~10-12 hPa), highest at sea level (~15 hPa).\n\nExtrapolation:\n  Flat() boundary: clamps queries outside the grid to nearest boundary value.\n  This matches interp.bilinear clamp semantics.\n\nNote on units:\n  The ESM parameters lon and lat are in degrees (the caller must convert from radians\n  if needed, matching the rad2deg calls in the original Julia function).\n\nTolerance rationale (rel=1e-6): bilinear blend over 4 grid points may incur rounding.\nGrid knots return exact table values; off-knot accumulates up to ~4 rounding steps."
      },
